Analysis of Genshin Impact: Are Gacha Rates Fair?

Vincent Ma, Farzad Mustafa, Aaron Kong

Motivation

Genshin Impact is an action role-playing video game developed by miHoYo, a Chinese gaming company. Introduced recently to the world on September 28, 2020, it captured many players to its open-world game. The games environment is set up in their own developed fantasy world that encompasses various weapons such as sword-wielding, elemental magic, dungeons, bosses, and character switching. The world consists of different regions that share subtle similarities to our real world. For example, the region Liyue, in the game, is inspired by Chinese culture. There are more regions as well such as Mondstadt and more to come in future updates and patch notes. Every player starts off their journey by picking one hero from the set of twins. Once acquired your character, you will start off your journey in the open world of Teyvat, the name of the world encompassing the regions. What is special to Genshin Impact that is different from other open-world, action, and fantasy games is its character swapping mechanics. Each player will be able to use up to four characters to their party as they go on their adventure. Each character having its own unique power and fighting abilities. For example, Diluc, a claymore pyro user, has different skills and fighting abilities when compared to Mona, a catalyst hydro user. Every playable character has their own backstory, which many people come to enjoy along with their fighting capabilities and appearances.

The question others will ask is how does this game generate revenue? The game is free-to-play, where any person who wants to play it just needs to download it from one of the offered playable devices which are on Android, iOS, Microsoft Windows, Playstation 4, Playstation 5, and soon to come to Nintendo Switch. It is free to download and you are able to experience all of the adventuring events and stories. However, the main source of revenue for miHoYo is one of the in-game currencies called Genesis Crystals. This special currency is obtained through real-world purchases or microtransactions. Where for the U.S. servers and currency, $0.99, $4.99, $14.99, $29.99, $49.99, and $99.99 will equate to 60, 300, 980, 1,980, 3,280, and 6,480 genesis crystals respectively. Now, the confusing part is that in our tutorial we will focus on Primogems, another in-game currency, as well as Acquaint and Intertwined fates. The reason we mention genesis crystals is that its the only currency that involves real-world money. Once you purchase genesis crystals for your account you are able to convert them into primogems. Primogems allows you to be able to pull for characters, such as Diluc or Mona. In the game, there are a variety of playable characters. Diluc and mona are known as 5 star characters, which are considered the rarest to acquire in the game. If you are not familiar with gacha systems, the higher the star rating a character or item is the rarer and generally more powerful it is. Likewise, if it is lower than a 5 star such as 4 star character or item, it will be comparatively less rare and weaker than a 5 star. For Genshin particularly, there are only 5 star and 4 star characters. Some of the 4 star characters, are obtainable through in-game as you progress through the story such as Amber and Kaeya. However, the other 4 star characters are obtainable through banners. Banners are a set of characters and weapons in which the player can roll on and will be given a random item from such a set.

To roll on a banner it will cost 160 primogems for 1 roll, so 1600 for 10 rolls. The player has the option of rolling one time or 10 times for any amount times as long they have enough primogems to spend. For example, rolling on a banner for one item will cost 160 and they will obtain an item based on the probabilities miHoYo enables for the banner. So, the reason the game has grossed over $1 billion within six months of release is largely due to the banner and rolling system. 5 star weapons and characters are sought after players, due to their rarity, and generally stronger stats. Not only that but the appearances of the characters and weapons too. Many people are willing to buy the in-game currency, genesis crystals, and convert those crystals to primogems. Once obtained the primogems are able to spend them on either acquaint or intertwined fates which is the item that is able to roll on a banner. Each type of fate costs 160 each and those two types are used for their respective banners. The intertwined fates are used for limited-time event banners that most people roll on. Therefore, the acquaint fates are used for the other banner known as the standard banner. The standard banner consists of a generally permanent set of 5 star characters and weapons where the banner will stay up permanently. The limited banner however only stays up for around a month where it holds exclusive limited time characters. Some examples of limited characters are Venti, Zhongli, and Klee. Additionally, these rolls or wishes, another term, for intertwined fates can also be used on a limited-time weapon banner as well. So, with the limited-time character banner and weapon banner, people will want to wish/roll on them to try to get a rare character or weapon. The limited-time character banner usually is exclusive to one 5 star promotional character. However, there is a chance you do not get the promotional character.

Chinese gaming companies are required by law to release the probability percentages to the public of the chances of getting a certain item. For Genshin Impact, the base rate for a 5 star character is 0.6% and the average rate including pity yields 1.6%. 4 star characters or weapons have a base rate of 5.1% and an average rate including pity of 13%. Lastly, 3 star weapons which is the lowest tier for weapons have a base rate of 94.3% and an average rate including pity of 85.4%. For the limited-time weapon wish banner, a 5 star weapon has a base rate of 0.7% and an average rate including pity of 1.85%. A 4 star character or weapon has a base rate of 6% and an average rate of 14.5%. The 3 star weapon has a rate of 93.3% and an average rate including pity of 83.65%. Pity is a hidden rate in the game where it increases the odds for pulling a better tier character/weapon the more time you wish/roll. There are also guarantees for the banner system which is one of the leniencies miHoYo provides to its players. For every banner, there is a 4 star drop guarantee where if a player does not win any 4 star or above item after 9 pulls, the 10th pull is guaranteed to be a 4 star or higher item. Furthermore, for the limited-time banner, there are featured 4 star characters of usually 3 characters as well as the promotional 5 star character. Every time a player wins a 4 star item there is a 50 percent chance it will be one of the featured 4 star characters. The 5 star drop guarantee is where if a player does not win any 5 star item after 89 pulls, the 90th pull is guaranteed to be a 5 star item. This counter will reset if the player pulls any 5 star item. The 5 promotional character guarantee, specifically for the limited time banner, is where for every time a player wins a 5 star item, there is a 50 percent chance it will be the promotional 5 star character. If the 5 star item won is not the promotional character, the next 5 star item is guaranteed to be the promotional character. Therefore, it requires a maximum of 180 pulls to win the promotional banner character.

These rates and the characters retrieved based on their respective rates will be tested amongst our own generated quantitative dataset to determine whether our assumptions and predictions match with our speculations. The motivation for conducting the data analysis tutorial for Genshin Impact is to determine if the rates of our own quantitive data match or are similar to the rates provided by the gaming company, miHoYo. The analysis and results may or may not determine if the probabilities the game states are accurate or fair for players. More importantly, the group members within this project each have their own personal stakes within Genshin. We each have spent our own money on the in-game currency which further emphasizes the importance of the data research on this study. Additionally, those we have sampled from friends and peers each have their own wealth invested in the game. Other external datasets with item information and wish information were analyzed as well. Finding the probabilities with our imported data from 3rd party providers and our analysis will determine the reliability of our notions towards the company and its game.

In [2]:
#Go though Web Export, split on ;
id = 1
label = ['Id','Banner','Item','Type','Rarity','Date']
rolls = pd.DataFrame(columns = label)
web_dir = "C:/Users/vzma/spring2021/CMSC320-Final-Tutorial/Data/WebExport"
for f in listdir(web_dir):
    if isfile(join(web_dir, f)):
        curr = pd.read_csv(join(web_dir, f))
        for index,line in curr.iterrows():
            temp = line[0].split(';')
            b = temp[0]
            if b=="Character Event":
                b = "Event"
            elif b=="Weapon Event":
                b = "Weapon"
            to_add = [id,b,temp[2],temp[3],int(temp[4]),temp[5][:-1].replace('T', ' ')]
            rolls.loc[len(rolls.index)] = to_add
        id = id+1

#Go though External Export get rid of stars
ext_dir = "C:/Users/vzma/spring2021/CMSC320-Final-Tutorial/Data/ExternalExport"
b = ['Character Event Wish History', 'Permanent Wish History', 'Weapon Event Wish History', 'Novice Wish History']
for f in listdir(ext_dir):
    if isfile(join(ext_dir, f)):
        notebook = pd.ExcelFile(join(ext_dir, f))
        for sheet in b:
            curr = pd.read_excel(notebook,sheet_name=sheet)
            for index,line in curr.iterrows():
                to_add = [id,line['Banner'],line['Item Name'],line['Item Type'],len(line['Item Rarity']),line['Date and Time']]
                rolls.loc[len(rolls.index)] = to_add
        id = id+1

Weapon Occurances

Organizes the weapons into a subset dataframe, categorizing each unique weapon with its name, rarity, and amount of wishes or claims it has based on the database. As you can see the weapons with the least rarity of 3 seem to have the most amount of wishes/count. Whereas the higher rarity weapons from 4 and 5 have a drastically lower amount of claims. For example, the Skyrider Sword of rarity 3 had 1467 wishes, whereas the Favonius Lance of the rarity of 4 has 86 wishes. The 5 star weapons were drastically lower however some had a noticeable difference compared to others such as Skyward Prides of 18 wishes had more claims compared to Memory of Dust with 1 wish. This could be reasonably inferred that limited-time weapons have a much lower rate of claims compared to permanently obtainable weapons for 5 stars.

In [7]:
weapons = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Item','Rarity','Count'])
temp = rolls.loc[rolls['Type']=='Weapon'].Item.unique()
for w in temp:
    r = rolls.loc[rolls['Item']==w]
    x = r['Rarity'].iloc[0]
    to_add = [w, x, len(r)]
    weapons.loc[len(weapons.index)] = to_add

Character Occurances

Now organizes the characters into a subset dataframe based on character name, rarity, and wishes. Again, the characters are sorted uniquely where the characters of 4 star rating has a general trend of higher counts compared to the 5 star. For example, Fischl of 4 star rarity has a count of 117 compared to Venti a 5 star of count 17. There are interesting results in our data. In particular, Keqing a 5 star has a count of 37 which is higher compared to Kaeya a 4 star of count 28. Furthermore, there are 5 stars with a drastically lower amount of wishes compared to other 5 stars such as Hu Tao of count 9 and Qiqi of count 23. One possibility of these differences could be due to the option of choosing a standard or limited-time banner and what the player would want. A key factor to mention is that Hu Tao is a limited available character whereas Qiqi could be acquired at any time. These noticeable differences will be further explained more, later on in the tutorial.

Rolling Frequency

Created a map database based on version, which categorizes character banners based on version/timeframe of the game. Maps are differentiated between versions starting from version v1.0 to v1.3. By utilizing the datetime and character banners timing, able to differentiate between the limited-time event banners. For example, the Venti banner, which is the very first limited-time banner, was introduced from September 28, 2020, to November 18, 2020. Then the Klee banner was introduced after another month. MiHoYo generally follows this cycle of limited-time banner monthly rotations, by following this pattern and knowing what specific character will be the promotion exclusive, will able to automate the versions database to respond to banner updates.

def makeList(lst,label,idx):
    temp = [idx,label]
    lst.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([(ix[0], str(ix[1])) for ix in lst.index.tolist()])
    try:
        temp.append(lst['Id'][('Weapon','3')])
    except Exception as e:
        temp.append(0)

    try:
        temp.append(lst['Id'][('Weapon','4')])
    except Exception as e:
        temp.append(0)

    try:
        temp.append(lst['Id'][('Weapon','5')])
    except Exception as e:
        temp.append(0)

    try:
        temp.append(lst['Id'][('Character','4')])
    except Exception as e:
        temp.append(0)

    try:
        temp.append(lst['Id'][('Character','5')])
    except Exception as e:
        temp.append(0)
    return temp

Data Analysis(Pie Charts)

The pie charts above demonstrate the rolling data for each banner across 21 different accounts. Starting from the Event Banner which corresponds to the leftmost pie chart, the data across all of these accounts seems to be consistent. An overwhelming amount of the rolls resulted in three star weapons, which is expected since they have the lowest rarity in the drop table, with a 94.3% chance to drop. Although the data is consistent here, the actual percentage of 3 star weapons that is similar across all the pie charts is around 84-85%. This is quite a bit lower than the 94.3% that Mihoyo tells on their website, but the lower percentage could be due to a lot of people getting the 5 star character they wanted through pity and stopping their rolls from there. The 5 star character rate for these banners is rather consistent as well, with the percentage being around 1 to 2.5, with ID 19 being the luckiest out of all of the players. 4 star characters are the second most commonly rolled category in this banner, as the three 4 star banner characters that are present have the highest chance to be rolled out of all 4 stars.

Now, onto the Weapon Banner, which is easily the least rolled banner in the data. This is due to the fact that 2 5 star weapons are present in each weapon banner, and a specific 5 star weapon is not guaranteed when rolling on the banner unlike the Character Event Banner, which guarantees the specified 5 star character in the banner once pity is reached. There have been cases of people spending over $1000 on a weapon banner, just to not end up with the weapon they wanted, and instead multiple of the other 5 star weapon. Since this banner is the least rolled, there are multiple people in the data who haven't rolled on it at all, or have minimal rolls on it, which means they probably rolled on that banner by accident. Those who have rolled on the banner, have similar 5 star rates to those on the Event Banner, although there are a few outliers present, as ID 17 had a 0.9% chance to roll a 5 star and ID 15 had a 2.8% chance to roll a 5 star. I think this is all due to the lack of volume present for the weapon banner compared to the Event Banners.

To the right of the Weapon Banner pie chart is the Permanent Banner. This banner is consistently the second most rolled banner in the data, as it never changes, hence the name Permanent Banner. The reason why it isn't the most rolled banner even if it is permanent is because of the risk involved. Unlike the weapon and event banner, the permanent banner does not guarantee a specific character or set of weapons. This makes it the riskiest banner in terms of obtaining specific characters or weapons. However, the reason that people still roll on this banner is because some specific characters are present in this banner and haven't had their own guaranteed banner yet. These characters include Diluc, Qiqi, Mona, and Jean. Although there is a chance to roll these characters in Event Banners, you have the highest probability of getting them in the Permanent Banner since limited time 5 stars in the Event Banner are not present in the Permanent Banner. The percentages for rolling a 5 star are consistent in this banner as seen on the pie charts, as they are around 1-2.5%. The split between 5 star weapons and 5 star characters for this banner is even as well for most of the data. The 4 star character and weapon split is also even in the data as well, with their total usually being around 13-15%.

The last banner, the pie chart on the far right, suffers similarly to the Weapon Banner, with there not being that high of a volume of rolls so the percentages are all over the place. This is because this Novice Banner can only be rolled 20 times at the beginning of the game, so the odds of getting a 5 star are very low as there is no pity involved in the novice banner. Some of the IDs have a 5 or 10% chance of rolling a 5 star, while others hadn't rolled a 5 star at all. Every person does have a guaranteed 4 star character, Noelle, from this banner however, which explains why the 4 star character rate was so high in this banner.

def plotHeat(item):
    counts = []
    for i in banners:
        r = []
        for j in items:
            temp = rolls.loc[rolls['Item']==j]
            count = 0
            for index, row in temp.iterrows():
                if charbanners[i][0]<=row['Date'] and row['Date']<=charbanners[i][1]:
                    count+=1
            r.append(count)
        if sum(r)!=0:
            r = [t / sum(r) for t in r]
        else:
            r = 0
        counts.append(r)

Heat Graph Analysis

The heat graph for the 3 star weapons that were rolled over the course of these event banners is very random, as expected. There are no guaranteed 3 star weapons like there are for characters in these banners. There are some weapons that were rolled more on specific banners, like Cool Steel on Venti's second banner, but that's simply due to chance. The heat graph for 4 star weapons are as expected as well, as the four star weapons all share extremely low percentages since none of them are guaranteed. The 3 banner 4 stars that are present in each of these banners were unsurprisingly rolled the most as well,for example Sucrose in Venti's second banner, with a rate of 0.32, which is by far the highest among any of the 4 stars present in this heat graph.
The third heat graph is where things get a little interesting. At first, everything seems normal, with no featured characters ending up on banners that they are not featured on. Their rates for their own banners seem to hover around 0.4-0.6, which indicates that the 50/50 rule is present. 5 star characters that don't have any featured banners such as Diluc and Mona are rolled with rather consistent rates, ranging from 0.04 to 0.12 per banner, with Diluc being the most consistent one.
Where things get interesting, however, is in Keqing's column, as she is by far the most rolled 5 star in this graph. The rate of getting her in her own banner was 1, opposed to 0.4-0.6 rates of all the other featured banners. This is probably due to Keqing's banner not being really rolled on at all, so the only people who did roll on her banner ended up getting her. The number of people who rolled on her banner are a very small fraction of people who rolled on other featured banners. What's most interesting is that Keqing was still rolled quite frequently on other featured banners, as she has the potential to be rolled since she had her own featured banner and is also present in the permanent banner. Keqing was rolled at a rate of 0.42 on Childe's banner, a banner in which Childe himself only had a rate of 0.31. This is weird, since he should have a way higher rate than someone who isn't even the featured 5 star on the banner. Keqing is also very prevalent in Klee's banner, where she had a rate of 0.3. All of the other non banner 5 stars never got to rates even close to this, which makes us believe that there might be something at play when it comes to rolling Keqing, since she's so common even though she's a regular 5 star.

In [ ]:
<center><h1>The Fifty Fifty Graph</h1></center>
This graph represents how many people have won the fifty-fifty when it comes rolling for a featured 5 star character on a banner. The fifty-fifty refers to there beinga 50% chance of getting the featured character on an event banner when you end up rolling a 5 star. If you lose the fifty-fifty, you get a different 5 star character. However, once you do lose, you are guaranteed whatever featured character there is on the banner next time you end up rolling a 5 star. This graph was created with this in mind, as it calculated how many people won or lost their fifty-fifty and how many times they did so. Once they lost a fifty-fifty, the next 5 star they rolled on that banner would be skipped, since it was guaranteed to be that character. This graph was made in order to see if the fifty-fifty rule that Mihoyo mentions is consistent, or if it's tipped in the company's favour so more people roll and spend money.

fiftyfifty = {}

for x in range(1,22):
    diff = 0
    curr = rolls.loc[rolls['Id']==x]
    event = curr.loc[curr['Banner'] =='Event'].loc[curr['Type']=='Character'].loc[curr['Rarity']==5]
    skip = False
    for index, row in event.iterrows():
        if skip is False and (row['Item'] in event_chars or (row['Item']=='Keqing' and charbanners['Keqing'][1]>=row['Date'] and charbanners['Keqing'][0]<=row['Date'])):
            diff+=1
            skip = False
        elif skip is False:
           diff-=1
           skip = True
    if diff not in fiftyfifty:
        fiftyfifty[diff] = 1
    else:
        fiftyfifty[diff]+=1

Fifty-Fifty Graph Analysis

The bar graph displaying how many times people won or lost the fifty-fifty is rather interesting. As expected, 0, which represents someone winning and losing the fifty-fifty an equal amount of times, is among the higher counts, but is still one less than -1, which represents someone losing the fifty-fifty one more time than winning it. Normally, this would a be little suspicious, but on the flipside, there's also data indicating that there are more people winning the fifty fifty than losing it. The columns indicating 1, 2, and 3, which all indicate winning the fifty-fifty that amount of times adds up to 8, which is more than the 7 in the -1 column. Overall, the fifty-fifty system seems to be fair for now, although it certainly does feel like we lose the fifty-fifty all the time.

Linear Regression of Number of Rolls per 5 Star

The function below counts how many rolls it took until a 5 star was rolled given a specific banner. Then, the average rate is calculated by getting the roll total from each of the banners using the function that was defined earlier, and dividing the sum by the length. The average rate is then fitted into a linear regression model, which calculated the regression line that corresponds to the number of rolls per five star. In the regression model we created, we ended up calculated a line that shows there being an average of aronud 59 rolls per 5 star, as shown by the intercept. The slope in this regression line is extremely small, but it's there to calculate whether or not rolling more, which is usually done by spending money, lowers the average amount of rolls per 5 star. Based on the regression line, it doesn't seem to have a tangible effect.

In [23]:
def countBanner(df):
    count = 0
    total = []
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        if row['Rarity']!=5:
            count+=1
        else:
            total.append(count)
            count = 0
    return total

    tot = rolls.loc[rolls['Id']==i].count()['Id']
    avgRate[tot] = sum(temp)/len(temp)

Calculating 4 Star and 5 Star Probabilities

The code below calculates the probability of rolling a 4 star and 5 star character given the rates for them provided by Mihoyo. The function below begins by setting the current pity for 4 stars to 9, and the current pity for 5 stars to 89. Each of these numbers signify 1 less than the pity, which is when a 4 star or 5 star character is guaranteed. For 4 stars, the pity number is 10, and for 5 stars, the pity number is 90. After setting the current pity, random numbers are generated 10,000,000 times. If pity is hit, or the randomly generated number is within the 5 star or 4 star probability, then the number of 5 star or 4 stars in total is incremented by 1. After that, the pity for 4 stars and/or 5 stars is reset back to 9 and 89 respectively.
The code after that runs this simulation another 50 times, which results in a total of 500,000,000 rolls via the random number generator. Once all of this is done, the total probability of getting a 5 star and a 4 star characters is calculated by dividing the sum by the length of the probability, as done before. The predicted rates from our simulation was 1.4% for five stars and 11.5% for four stars. The overall rates calculated by this random number generated seem to be different from the percentages Mihoyo claims for 5 star and 4 stars, 1.6% and 13% respectively.

In [26]:
def checkProb():
    num4 = 0
    num5 = 0
    cur_pity4 = 9
    cur_pity5 = 89
    for i in range(10000000):
        rand = random.random()
        if rand < .006 or cur_pity5 <= 0:
            num5 += 1
            cur_pity4 = 9
            cur_pity5 = 89
        elif rand < 0.051 or cur_pity4 <= 0:
            num4 += 1
            cur_pity4 = 9
            cur_pity5 -= 1
        else:
            cur_pity4 -= 1
            cur_pity5 -= 1
    return ((num4 / 10000000 * 100), (num5 / 10000000 * 100))

I got Keqing as my seventh roll on the novice banner. This only allows for five different five stars to be rooled so the calculation is as follows: (.94)^6 .06.2 = .82784%

This leads to the combining all these together .0082784 x .05 x .0000008704895 = 3.6031464e-10 = .0000000036031464% = 1/27,753,688,800. Though this is the chance of my specific scenario, the highest chance of getting seven Keqings is still very low. The highest chance of getting all seven Keqings from the event banner would be (.5*.2)^7 = 1.0e-7. For the permanent banner it would be (1/15)^7 = 5.85e-9. To put these numbers to scale the chance of being struck by lightning is 1/114195, the chance of being attacked by a shark is 1/3748067, and the chance of winning the Powerball jackpot is 1/292,000,000. My initial calculation is roughly a hundred times less likely to occur than winning the lottery. So what does all this mean? It means I am extremely lucky but in the worst way possible.
